[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01G3U8QuyWS5Hg1yBVrGSh9C","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WXco2wFouErhx2omioKze3","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3367,"cache_read_input_tokens":13948,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3367,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa","uuid":"ea8c08cd-489b-4d84-8166-fed42b609a20"}
[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01D9PLj39KZbK4a35Mhe1GY2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Host Workflow Design (`host.cloche`)\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-06\n     4→**Status:** Design\n     5→\n     6→## Problem\n     7→\n     8→The orchestrator's intake → process → output loop is hard-coded in Go\n     9→(`internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go`). Every project must follow the same flow:\n    10→pull task → generate prompt → dispatch `develop` container run. This can't be changed\n    11→without modifying Cloche itself. Projects that need different orchestration strategies\n    12→(push to GitHub for review, group tickets into feature branches, stacked commits, etc.)\n    13→have no extension point.\n    14→\n    15→## Solution: `host.cloche`\n    16→\n    17→A special workflow file at `.cloche/host.cloche`. It uses the same DSL as container\n    18→workflow files, with one additional step type (`workflow`). Steps in this file execute\n    19→on the **host machine**, not inside a container.\n    20→\n    21→The workflow named `main` in this file becomes the per-task orchestration loop\n    22→for that project. The Go daemon becomes the executor of this workflow rather than the\n    23→hard-coded logic holder.\n    24→\n    25→### File location\n    26→\n    27→```\n    28→.cloche/host.cloche\n    29→```\n    30→\n    31→If the file does not exist, the daemon falls back to the current hard-coded behavior\n    32→(pull task → LLM prompt generation → dispatch container workflow).\n    33→\n    34→---\n    35→\n    36→## DSL additions\n    37→\n    38→### New step type: `workflow`\n    39→\n    40→A step with `workflow_name` config key is a workflow-dispatch step. It dispatches a\n    41→named container workflow run and blocks until that run completes.\n    42→\n    43→```\n    44→step develop {\n    45→  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    46→  results = [success, fail]\n    47→}\n    48→```\n    49→\n    50→`workflow_name` is added to `knownStepConfigKeys` in `domain/workflow.go`.\n    51→\n    52→`StepTypeWorkflow` is added to the `StepType` enum in `domain/workflow.go`.\n    53→\n    54→The parser (`dsl/parser.go`) infers `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` is present\n    55→(same pattern as `run` → script, `prompt` → agent).\n    56→\n    57→### Prompt input for `workflow` steps\n    58→\n    59→The container workflow needs a prompt. By convention, a `workflow` step reads the\n    60→previous step's captured output file as the prompt. This is the primary data-passing\n    61→mechanism.\n    62→\n    63→An optional config key `prompt_step` overrides which step's output to read:\n    64→```\n    65→step develop {\n    66→  workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    67→  prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    68→  results       = [success, fail]\n    69→}\n    70→```\n    71→\n    72→---\n    73→\n    74→## Step output capture\n    75→\n    76→Every step in a host workflow execution writes its output (stdout of `run` steps,\n    77→final response of `prompt` steps) to a file:\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→.cloche/<orch-run-id>/main/<step_name>.out\n    81→```\n    82→\n    83→`<orch-run-id>` is a unique ID for this orchestration invocation, formatted the same\n    84→way as workflow run IDs (e.g. `main-bold-hawk`).\n    85→\n    86→The daemon tracks the most recently completed step's output path and passes it to the\n    87→next step as `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT`.\n    88→\n    89→---\n    90→\n    91→## Environment variables injected into host steps\n    92→\n    93→All `run` and `prompt` steps receive:\n    94→\n    95→| Variable | Value |\n    96→|----------|-------|\n    97→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID being processed |\n    98→| `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE` | Task summary/title |\n    99→| `CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` | Task full body/description |\n   100→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory |\n   101→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output |\n   102→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the previous step's output file |\n   103→\n   104→For `workflow` steps, `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` is read automatically (unless `prompt_step`\n   105→overrides it).\n   106→\n   107→---\n   108→\n   109→## Executor: `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go`\n   110→\n   111→New file. Implements the host workflow execution loop.\n   112→\n   113→```go\n   114→type HostRunner struct {\n   115→    Dispatch  RunDispatcher      // existing: dispatches a container workflow run\n   116→    WaitRun   RunWaiter          // new: blocks until a run ID completes, returns final state\n   117→    AgentCmd  string             // command to invoke for prompt steps on host\n   118→}\n   119→\n   120→// RunWorkflow executes the named workflow from a parsed host.cloche Workflow\n   121→// for a single task. Returns the final result (\"done\" or \"abort\").\n   122→func (r *HostRunner) RunWorkflow(ctx context.Context, wf *domain.Workflow, task ports.Task, orchRunID string) (string, error)\n   123→```\n   124→\n   125→Step execution:\n   126→\n   127→- **`script` step** (`run` key): `exec.Command` with env vars, stdout captured to\n   128→  `<step>.out`, stderr to `<step>.err`. Exit 0 → `success`, non-zero → `fail`.\n   129→- **`agent` step** (`prompt` key): invoke `AgentCmd` on host with the prompt file\n   130→  contents injected. Capture output. Exit 0 → `success`, non-zero → `fail`.\n   131→- **`workflow` step** (`workflow_name` key): read prompt from prev step's `.out` file\n   132→  (or `prompt_step` override), call `Dispatch`, then call `WaitRun` to block until\n   133→  the container run completes. Map `succeeded` → `success`, `failed`/`cancelled` →\n   134→  `fail`.\n   135→\n   136→`WaitRun` is a new port interface:\n   137→\n   138→```go\n   139→// RunWaiter blocks until the run with the given ID reaches a terminal state.\n   140→type RunWaiter interface {\n   141→    WaitRun(ctx context.Context, runID string) (domain.RunState, error)\n   142→}\n   143→```\n   144→\n   145→The gRPC server / store already has `GetRun`; the waiter can poll it with backoff or\n   146→subscribe to the `OnRunComplete` event. A simple polling implementation (1s interval)\n   147→is sufficient initially.\n   148→\n   149→---\n   150→\n   151→## Refactored `orchestrator.Orchestrator`\n   152→\n   153→`Orchestrator.Run()` is updated:\n   154→\n   155→**Current flow (hardcoded):**\n   156→1. Pull ready tasks\n   157→2. Claim task\n   158→3. Call `promptGen.Generate(task)`\n   159→4. Call `dispatch(workflow, projectDir, prompt)` → runID\n   160→5. (In-flight counter managed, `OnRunComplete` decrements it)\n   161→\n   162→**New flow (when `host.cloche` exists):**\n   163→1. Pull ready tasks\n   164→2. Claim task\n   165→3. Parse `.cloche/host.cloche` → find `main` workflow\n   166→4. Generate an `orchRunID` (`main-<namegen>`)\n   167→5. Spin up a goroutine: call `hostRunner.RunWorkflow(ctx, orch wf, task, orchRunID)`\n   168→6. On goroutine return: decrement in-flight, update task state (success/fail)\n   169→\n   170→The old `promptGen` and `dispatch` are still used as the **fallback** when\n   171→`host.cloche` is absent (no breaking change for existing projects).\n   172→\n   173→`WaitRun` needs access to the run store. Wire it in `initOrchestrator` in\n   174→`cmd/cloched/main.go`.\n   175→\n   176→---\n   177→\n   178→## Default `host.cloche` (from `cloche init`)\n   179→\n   180→```\n   181→# host.cloche — orchestration workflow (runs on host, not in container)\n   182→# Steps here execute as the daemon user. Keep operations simple and safe.\n   183→\n   184→workflow \"main\" {\n   185→  step prepare-prompt {\n   186→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   187→    results = [success, fail]\n   188→  }\n   189→\n   190→  step develop {\n   191→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   192→    results       = [success, fail]\n   193→  }\n   194→\n   195→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   196→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   197→  develop:success        -> done\n   198→  develop:fail           -> done\n   199→}\n   200→```\n   201→\n   202→And `.cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` (created by init, chmod +x):\n   203→\n   204→```bash\n   205→#!/usr/bin/env bash\n   206→# Default prompt generator. Uses task env vars injected by cloched.\n   207→# Write the prompt to $CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT (also echoed to stdout).\n   208→set -euo pipefail\n   209→\n   210→prompt=\"## Task: ${CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE}\n   211→\n   212→${CLOCHE_TASK_BODY}\"\n   213→\n   214→echo \"$prompt\"\n   215→[ -n \"${CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT:-}\" ] && echo \"$prompt\" > \"$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT\"\n   216→```\n   217→\n   218→---\n   219→\n   220→## `.gitignore` update\n   221→\n   222→`cloche init` adds `.cloche/scripts/` is NOT gitignored (scripts are project config).\n   223→The orchestration run output dirs follow the same pattern as container run dirs:\n   224→`.cloche/main-*/` is gitignored via the existing `.cloche/*/` rule.\n   225→\n   226→---\n   227→\n   228→## Safety notes\n   229→\n   230→- Host steps run with the same OS privileges as the `cloched` process.\n   231→- No network isolation.\n   232→- `host.cloche` should only reference scripts that are committed to the project.\n   233→- Document that `prompt` steps in `host.cloche` invoke an LLM agent with full host\n   234→  filesystem access — use judiciously.\n   235→\n   236→---\n   237→\n   238→## Changes required\n   239→\n   240→| File | Change |\n   241→|------|--------|\n   242→| `internal/domain/workflow.go` | Add `StepTypeWorkflow`, add `workflow_name`/`prompt_step` to `knownStepConfigKeys` |\n   243→| `internal/dsl/parser.go` | Infer `StepTypeWorkflow` when `workflow_name` key is present |\n   244→| `internal/orchestrator/hostrunner.go` | New: host workflow executor |\n   245→| `internal/orchestrator/orchestrator.go` | Refactor `Run()` to use `HostRunner` when `host.cloche` exists; fall back to current behavior otherwise |\n   246→| `internal/ports/container.go` | Add `RunWaiter` interface |\n   247→| `cmd/cloched/main.go` | Wire `HostRunner` into orchestrator init |\n   248→| `cmd/cloche/init.go` | Create `host.cloche` and `scripts/prepare-prompt.sh` |\n   249→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa","uuid":"5b300487-84d6-4842-884d-072585326400"}
[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WXco2wFouErhx2omioKze3","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Workflows\n     2→\n     3→Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4→\n     5→## Workflow Locations\n     6→\n     7→Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8→\n     9→**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\n    10→container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11→standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12→\n    13→**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14→process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15→dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16→point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17→\n    18→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20→\n    21→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22→|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26→\n    27→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28→single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29→\n    30→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31→object with the following fields:\n    32→\n    33→| Field | Required | Description |\n    34→|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38→| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40→\n    41→The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42→compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43→Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44→reassignment.\n    45→\n    46→The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47→file is a parse error.\n    48→\n    49→## Concepts\n    50→\n    51→| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52→|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53→| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54→| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55→| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56→| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57→| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n    58→| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n    59→\n    60→## Step Types\n    61→\n    62→Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63→\n    64→**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65→to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66→container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67→\n    68→**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69→any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70→\n    71→**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72→until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73→\n    74→A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75→parse error.\n    76→\n    77→## DSL Syntax\n    78→\n    79→```\n    80→workflow \"develop\" {\n    81→  container {\n    82→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n    83→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n    84→  }\n    85→\n    86→  step implement {\n    87→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    88→    results = [success, fail]\n    89→  }\n    90→\n    91→  step test {\n    92→    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    93→    results = [success, fail]\n    94→  }\n    95→\n    96→  step fix {\n    97→    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    98→    max_attempts = \"3\"\n    99→    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n   100→  }\n   101→\n   102→  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   103→  implement:success -> test\n   104→  implement:fail    -> abort\n   105→  test:success      -> done\n   106→  test:fail         -> fix\n   107→  fix:success       -> test\n   108→  fix:fail          -> abort\n   109→  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   110→}\n   111→```\n   112→\n   113→## Key Properties\n   114→\n   115→**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   116→field makes it a script step.\n   117→\n   118→**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   119→report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   120→\n   121→**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   122→existing ones by rewiring — without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   123→Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   124→\n   125→**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   126→wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   127→\n   128→## Wire Output Mappings\n   129→\n   130→Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   131→them as environment variables into the target step:\n   132→\n   133→```\n   134→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   135→```\n   136→\n   137→The general form:\n   138→\n   139→```\n   140→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   141→```\n   142→\n   143→Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   144→starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   145→\n   146→| Expression | Meaning |\n   147→|---|---|\n   148→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   149→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   150→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   151→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   152→| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   153→\n   154→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   155→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   156→value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   157→\n   158→If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   159→returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   160→wires to different steps without conflict.\n   161→\n   162→## Workflow-Level Configuration Blocks\n   163→\n   164→Workflows support a configuration block at the workflow level to set defaults for all\n   165→steps. The block name depends on the workflow location:\n   166→\n   167→**`container {}`** — For container workflows. Sets container image, agent command, and\n   168→network allowlist.\n   169→\n   170→```\n   171→workflow \"develop\" {\n   172→  container {\n   173→    image = \"my-project:latest\"\n   174→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   175→    agent_args = \"-p --dangerously-skip-permissions\"\n   176→  }\n   177→  ...\n   178→}\n   179→```\n   180→\n   181→Supported keys: `image`, `agent_command`, `agent_args`, `network_allow`.\n   182→\n   183→**`host {}`** — For host workflows (`host.cloche`). Sets agent defaults for agent steps\n   184→running on the host machine.\n   185→\n   186→```\n   187→workflow \"main\" {\n   188→  host {\n   189→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   190→  }\n   191→  ...\n   192→}\n   193→```\n   194→\n   195→Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`.\n   196→\n   197→Step-level `agent_command` and `agent_args` override workflow-level defaults. The\n   198→resolution order is: step-level > workflow-level block > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env\n   199→var > default `claude`.\n   200→\n   201→## Host Workflow Example\n   202→\n   203→A three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   204→workflows:\n   205→\n   206→```\n   207→# .cloche/host.cloche — runs on the host machine\n   208→\n   209→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   210→  step fetch-tickets {\n   211→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   212→    results = [success, fail]\n   213→  }\n   214→\n   215→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   216→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   217→}\n   218→\n   219→workflow \"main\" {\n   220→  host {\n   221→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   222→  }\n   223→\n   224→  step prepare-prompt {\n   225→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   226→    results = [success, fail]\n   227→  }\n   228→\n   229→  step develop {\n   230→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   231→    results       = [success, fail]\n   232→  }\n   233→\n   234→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   235→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   236→  develop:success        -> done\n   237→  develop:fail           -> done\n   238→}\n   239→\n   240→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   241→  step push-for-review {\n   242→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   243→    results = [success, fail]\n   244→  }\n   245→\n   246→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   247→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   248→}\n   249→```\n   250→\n   251→The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   252→runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   253→The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   254→The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   255→The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   256→`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   257→\n   258→## Execution Model\n   259→\n   260→**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   261→container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   262→wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   263→All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   264→\n   265→**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   266→`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   267→in three phases (list-tasks → main → finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   268→working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   269→if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   270→host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   271→runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   272→`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   273→points to the actual project directory.\n   274→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa","uuid":"8b782629-bc3b-4e6d-83e2-f06ecc9af9d7"}
