[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01LYLVRuXcSpay2gnd5TCzAE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014vrbq2bHTe9Zc621zhMsSX","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"git show 3ab35fb:docs/workflows.md 2>/dev/null | head -80"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2690,"cache_read_input_tokens":47167,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2690,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa","uuid":"6a779bd3-a5c5-468a-9056-df1915bec001"}
[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014vrbq2bHTe9Zc621zhMsSX","type":"tool_result","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) — Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) — Run on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\nsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\ncompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\nTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\nreassignment.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step — successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step — failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) — Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) — Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) — Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa","uuid":"14ef35ec-cdc6-4b17-b87c-27cfa7139add"}
[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"system","subtype":"task_progress","task_id":"a0d58d07d5e793475","tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","description":"Reading docs/plans/2026-03-09-wire-output-mapping-design.md","usage":{"total_tokens":49929,"tool_uses":25,"duration_ms":19794},"last_tool_name":"Read","uuid":"7e6c954d-d4d1-4eaf-92da-9ee7991e9d88","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa"}
[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01LYLVRuXcSpay2gnd5TCzAE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014PJQxeB86BanYTDChuqmYn","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/workspace/docs/plans/2026-03-09-wire-output-mapping-design.md","limit":100},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2690,"cache_read_input_tokens":47167,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2690,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa","uuid":"53603b3b-d767-436e-8eed-bcd5c9b7d8ca"}
[2026-03-13T17:38:19Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014PJQxeB86BanYTDChuqmYn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Wire Output Mapping\n     2→\n     3→**Date:** 2026-03-09\n     4→**Status:** Proposed\n     5→\n     6→## Problem\n     7→\n     8→Host workflow steps produce output that downstream steps need as structured\n     9→input. Today the only mechanism is `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT`, a file path to the\n    10→previous step's raw output. Steps that need specific fields must parse the\n    11→output themselves, and there's no way to express \"extract field X from step A's\n    12→JSON output and inject it as env var Y into step B\" in the DSL.\n    13→\n    14→This came up immediately: `ready-tasks` outputs JSON from `bd ready --json`,\n    15→and `prepare-prompt` needs `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE` and `CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` as env\n    16→vars. Without DSL-level mapping, every step needs bespoke shell glue.\n    17→\n    18→## Design\n    19→\n    20→### Syntax\n    21→\n    22→Output mappings live on wires, not on step declarations. A wire describes data\n    23→flow between two steps, so the mapping belongs there:\n    24→\n    25→```\n    26→step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n    27→```\n    28→\n    29→The general form:\n    30→\n    31→```\n    32→FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n    33→```\n    34→\n    35→Where:\n    36→- `KEY` is the environment variable name injected into the target step\n    37→- `EXPR` is an output path expression (see below)\n    38→\n    39→### Output Path Expressions\n    40→\n    41→All expressions start with `output`, which refers to the source step's output.\n    42→\n    43→| Expression | Meaning |\n    44→|---|---|\n    45→| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n    46→| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n    47→| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n    48→| `output.key[N]` | Chained: field then index |\n    49→| `output[N].key` | Chained: index then field |\n    50→| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n    51→| `output.a[0].b[1].c` | Arbitrary nesting |\n    52→\n    53→If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n    54→structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid — any `.key`\n    55→or `[N]` access is a runtime error.\n    56→\n    57→The resolved value is always converted to a string for injection as an env var.\n    58→JSON objects and arrays are re-serialized as JSON strings. Scalars use their\n    59→natural string representation.\n    60→\n    61→### Examples\n    62→\n    63→```\n    64→workflow \"main\" {\n    65→  step get-tasks {\n    66→    run     = \"bd ready --json --limit 1\"\n    67→    results = [success, fail]\n    68→  }\n    69→\n    70→  step prepare-prompt {\n    71→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    72→    results = [success, fail]\n    73→  }\n    74→\n    75→  step develop {\n    76→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    77→    results       = [success, fail]\n    78→  }\n    79→\n    80→  get-tasks:success -> prepare-prompt [\n    81→    CLOCHE_TASK_ID    = output[0].id,\n    82→    CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE = output[0].title,\n    83→    CLOCHE_TASK_BODY  = output[0].description\n    84→  ]\n    85→  get-tasks:fail       -> abort\n    86→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n    87→  develop:success        -> done\n    88→  develop:fail           -> abort\n    89→}\n    90→```\n    91→\n    92→Multiple wires into the same step merge their mappings. If two wires map the\n    93→same key, that's a validation error (ambiguous).\n    94→\n    95→### Interaction with CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT\n    96→\n    97→`CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` continues to work as before — it always points to the\n    98→previous step's raw output file. Output mappings are additive: they inject\n    99→extra env vars alongside the existing ones. A step can use both the mapped\n   100→vars and read the raw file if needed."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0174MVnqQzdA1TA2bgz29vUa","session_id":"1b08d49b-02d1-4c4d-80e7-fef14e91a7aa","uuid":"84e3364e-a86a-4ced-8df4-6cd0e4ccc67e"}
