[2026-03-13T17:40:09Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BsianePxiGm5ZmUoNCKcWf","type":"tool_result","content":"   265→Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\n   266→dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\n   267→execute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\n   268→fixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n   269→\n   270→A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n   271→uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n   272→\n   273→| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n   274→|-------|--------------|---------|\n   275→| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n   276→| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n   277→| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n   278→\n   279→Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\n   280→mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n   281→\n   282→### list-tasks Output Format\n   283→\n   284→The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n   285→object:\n   286→\n   287→| Field | Required | Description |\n   288→|-------|----------|-------------|\n   289→| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n   290→| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n   291→| `title` | no | Short summary |\n   292→| `description` | no | Full description |\n   293→| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n   294→\n   295→The daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\n   296→set in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\n   297→deduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n   298→\n   299→### Host Workflow Example\n   300→\n   301→A three-phase `host.cloche`:\n   302→\n   303→```\n   304→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   305→  step fetch-tickets {\n   306→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   307→    results = [success, fail]\n   308→  }\n   309→\n   310→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   311→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   312→}\n   313→\n   314→workflow \"main\" {\n   315→  host {\n   316→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   317→  }\n   318→\n   319→  step prepare-prompt {\n   320→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   321→    results = [success, fail]\n   322→  }\n   323→\n   324→  step develop {\n   325→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   326→    results       = [success, fail]\n   327→  }\n   328→\n   329→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   330→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   331→  develop:success        -> done\n   332→  develop:fail           -> done\n   333→}\n   334→\n   335→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   336→  step push-for-review {\n   337→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   338→    results = [success, fail]\n   339→  }\n   340→\n   341→  push-for-review:success -> done\n   342→  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   343→}\n   344→```\n   345→\n   346→The `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\n   347→receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\n   348→workflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\n   349→what cleanup to perform.\n   350→\n   351→### Host Step Environment Variables\n   352→\n   353→| Variable | Description |\n   354→|----------|-------------|\n   355→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n   356→| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n   357→| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n   358→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   359→| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n   360→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   361→| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n   362→| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n   363→\n   364→### Container Environment Variables\n   365→\n   366→| Variable | Description |\n   367→|----------|-------------|\n   368→| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n   369→| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n   370→| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n   371→| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n   372→\n   373→## Setting Up Host Workflows\n   374→\n   375→The `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\n   376→When you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\n   377→generated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\n   378→to automate task discovery and cleanup.\n   379→\n   380→The daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n   381→\n   382→1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n   383→2. **`main`** — execute the work\n   384→3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n   385→\n   386→All three workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\n   387→required; `list-tasks` and `finalize` are optional.\n   388→\n   389→### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n   390→\n   391→The `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\n   392→tracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n   393→\n   394→**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\n   395→loop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n   396→\n   397→**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n   398→`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n   399→\n   400→```json\n   401→{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n   402→{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   403→{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n   404→```\n   405→\n   406→The daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\n   407→Tasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n   408→5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n   409→\n   410→**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n   411→\n   412→```\n   413→workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   414→  step fetch-tickets {\n   415→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   416→    results = [success, fail]\n   417→  }\n   418→\n   419→  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   420→  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   421→}\n   422→```\n   423→\n   424→**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\n   425→once without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\n   426→runs manually with `cloche run`.\n   427→\n   428→### `main` — Executing Work\n   429→\n   430→The `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n   431→`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n   432→\n   433→**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\n   434→is absent). The daemon sets `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE`, and\n   435→`CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` environment variables from the selected task.\n   436→\n   437→**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\n   438→then dispatches a container workflow:\n   439→\n   440→```\n   441→workflow \"main\" {\n   442→  host {\n   443→    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   444→  }\n   445→\n   446→  step prepare-prompt {\n   447→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   448→    results = [success, fail]\n   449→  }\n   450→\n   451→  step develop {\n   452→    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   453→    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n   454→    results       = [success, fail]\n   455→  }\n   456→\n   457→  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   458→  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   459→  develop:success        -> done\n   460→  develop:fail           -> done\n   461→}\n   462→```\n   463→\n   464→The `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\n   465→it completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\n   466→used as the prompt for the container run.\n   467→\n   468→You can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n   469→`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n   470→`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n   471→\n   472→### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n   473→\n   474→The `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\n   475→of whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n   476→\n   477→**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\n   478→sets two additional environment variables:\n   479→\n   480→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n   481→- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n   482→\n   483→**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n   484→\n   485→```\n   486→workflow \"finalize\" {\n   487→  step close-task {\n   488→    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n   489→    results = [success, fail]\n   490→  }\n   491→\n   492→  close-task:success -> done\n   493→  close-task:fail    -> done\n   494→}\n   495→```\n   496→\n   497→A typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\n   498→closing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\n   499→Wiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\n   500→finalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n   501→\n   502→**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\n   503→don't need automated cleanup.\n   504→\n   505→### Putting It All Together\n   506→\n   507→The three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n   508→\n   509→1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n   510→2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n   511→3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n   512→4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n   513→5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n   514→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"832f6df2-1a53-47c0-b762-a9ee0142818b","uuid":"81fbb44b-ef73-4eba-aae1-a2c3efd439a0","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/USAGE.md","content":"Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow_name` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and blocks until it completes. Script steps\nexecute with their working directory set to the main git worktree, so host-workflow\nfixes on main are available to in-flight runs even if they branched earlier.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a single-workflow\nmode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\n### list-tasks Output Format\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open`, runs `main` with that task's ID\nset in `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, then runs `finalize` with the outcome. Tasks are\ndeduplicated within a timeout window to prevent rapid reassignment of the same task.\n\n### Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche`:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `list-tasks` script writes JSONL to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. The `main` workflow\nreceives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket. The `finalize`\nworkflow receives `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars to decide\nwhat cleanup to perform.\n\n### Host Step Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Absolute path to the project directory on the host. |\n| `CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT` | Path where this step should write its output (for output mappings). |\n| `CLOCHE_PREV_OUTPUT` | Path to the output file from the immediately preceding step. |\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` | Task ID assigned by the daemon (set for `main` and `finalize` phases). |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` | Result of the `main` workflow (`succeeded` or `failed`). Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` | Run ID of the completed `main` workflow. Set for `finalize` phase only. |\n| Wire-mapped vars | Any env vars declared in wire output mappings. |\n\n### Container Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Description |\n|----------|-------------|\n| `CLOCHE_RUN_ID` | The run ID for this workflow execution. |\n| `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` | Working directory (set for script steps so `cloche get`/`cloche set` work). |\n| `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` | Passed through from the host if set. |\n| `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` | Overrides the default agent command inside the container. |\n\n## Setting Up Host Workflows\n\nThe `host.cloche` file is the orchestration layer that ties everything together.\nWhen you run `cloche init`, a minimal `host.cloche` with just a `main` workflow is\ngenerated. As your project grows, you can add `list-tasks` and `finalize` workflows\nto automate task discovery and cleanup.\n\nThe daemon recognizes three workflow names in `host.cloche` and runs them in order:\n\n1. **`list-tasks`** — discover available work\n2. **`main`** — execute the work\n3. **`finalize`** — clean up after the work completes\n\nAll three workflows live in the same `.cloche/host.cloche` file. Only `main` is\nrequired; `list-tasks` and `finalize` are optional.\n\n### `list-tasks` — Discovering Work\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow runs first. Its job is to query your task tracker (issue\ntracker, project board, ticket queue, etc.) and output a list of available tasks.\n\n**When it runs:** The daemon calls `list-tasks` at the start of each orchestration\nloop iteration, before launching any new `main` runs.\n\n**Output format:** The final step must write JSONL (one JSON object per line) to\n`$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`. Each line represents a task:\n\n```json\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-42\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"Users report...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-43\", \"status\": \"in-progress\", \"title\": \"Add caching\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n{\"id\": \"PROJ-44\", \"status\": \"open\", \"title\": \"Update docs\", \"description\": \"...\"}\n```\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with `status: \"open\"` and passes it to `main`.\nTasks that were recently assigned are deduplicated within a timeout window (default\n5 minutes) to prevent the same task from being picked repeatedly.\n\n**How to configure:** Write a script that queries your task source and outputs JSONL:\n\n```\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n```\n\n**If omitted:** The daemon falls back to single-workflow mode — it runs `main`\nonce without task assignment. This is fine for simple use cases where you trigger\nruns manually with `cloche run`.\n\n### `main` — Executing Work\n\nThe `main` workflow does the actual work. This is the only required workflow in\n`host.cloche` and is always generated by `cloche init`.\n\n**When it runs:** After `list-tasks` selects a task (or immediately if `list-tasks`\nis absent). The daemon sets `CLOCHE_TASK_ID`, `CLOCHE_TASK_TITLE`, and\n`CLOCHE_TASK_BODY` environment variables from the selected task.\n\n**How to configure:** A typical `main` workflow prepares a prompt from the task data,\nthen dispatches a container workflow:\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    prompt_step   = \"prepare-prompt\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe `workflow_name` step type dispatches a container workflow run and blocks until\nit completes. Use `prompt_step` to specify which preceding step's output should be\nused as the prompt for the container run.\n\nYou can add steps before or after the container workflow — for example, a\n`claim-task` step to mark the task as in-progress in your tracker, or a\n`merge-to-main` step to merge the result branch.\n\n### `finalize` — Post-Run Cleanup\n\nThe `finalize` workflow handles cleanup after `main` completes. It runs regardless\nof whether `main` succeeded or failed.\n\n**When it runs:** Immediately after `main` finishes (success or failure). The daemon\nsets two additional environment variables:\n\n- `CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` — `\"succeeded\"` or `\"failed\"`\n- `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` — the run ID of the completed `main` workflow\n\n**How to configure:** Use the outcome to decide what cleanup to perform:\n\n```\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step close-task {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/close-task.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  close-task:success -> done\n  close-task:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nA typical `finalize` script checks `$CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and acts accordingly —\nclosing the ticket on success, or posting a failure comment for investigation.\nWiring both results to `done` (not `abort`) ensures the daemon treats the\nfinalize phase as complete regardless of the cleanup script's exit status.\n\n**If omitted:** The daemon skips the finalize phase entirely. This is fine if you\ndon't need automated cleanup.\n\n### Putting It All Together\n\nThe three-phase model enables fully automated task pipelines:\n\n1. The orchestration loop calls `list-tasks` to find open work\n2. It picks an open task and launches `main` with the task context\n3. `main` prepares a prompt, dispatches a container workflow, and optionally merges results\n4. `finalize` closes the ticket or reports failure\n5. The loop repeats, picking the next open task\n","numLines":250,"startLine":265,"totalLines":809}}}
